DWELLING_TYPE_DESCRIPTION: A structure originally designed and built to contain a single dwelling unit.
A structure originally designed and built to contain two dwelling units, either side-by-side, front-to-back or one above the other.
A structure originally designed and built to contain at least three dwelling units on one or two levels. The dwelling units share outside entrances.
A structure originally designed and built to contain at least three dwelling units on three or more levels. The dwelling units share outside entrances.
A structure originally designed and built to contain three or more attached, or semi-attached dwelling units, each of which has a separate outside entrance.
A structure originally built to be movable whether it is now movable or on a permanent foundation. Include summer travel trailers only if used as a permanent residence.
The additional dwelling units in a structure that contains more units than the building was originally designed and built to contain.
A structure that ontains one dwelling unit, which accommodates multiple individuals who have separate sleeping facilities but share common cooking and/or bathroom facilities.
A structure that is primarily commercial but which also contains one or two dwelling units.
Any residential structure that contains a dwelling unit which does not fit the other structure codes, e.g. shack, garage.

A structure originally designed and built to contain one or more dwelling units which is designated as a nursing home, auxiliary hospital, care centre, lodge, etec. There are many seniors' residences being constructed that have suites with a bathroom and kitchenette containing a sink, bar fridge, microwave, etc. The suite must contain a full size fridge and stove to be considered as a separate dwelling unit. Otherwise, all suites included at one address and are part of this definition for lodges, care centres, or assisted living.
A structure where multiple residents are temporarily living and where the cooking is centrally provided for and which is not prepared by the residents, e.g. hospice, jail, etc.
A structure that provides lodging.

A structure that is primarily commercial but which also contains one or two dwelling units.
Any residential structure that contains a dwelling unit which does not fit the other structure codes, e.g. shack, garage.

A structure originally designed and built to contain one or more dwelling units which is designated as a nursing home, auxiliary hospital, care centre, lodge, etec. A structure originally designed and built to contain at least three dwelling units on three or more levels. The dwelling units share outside entrances.
A structure originally designed and built to contain three or more attached, or semi-attached dwelling units, each of which has a separate outside entrance.
A structure originally built to be movable whether it is now movable or on a permanent foundation. Include summer travel trailers only if used as a permanent residence.
The additional dwelling units in a structure that contains more units than the building was originally designed and built to contain.
A structure that ontains one dwelling unit, which accommodates multiple individuals who have separate sleeping facilities but share common cooking and/or bathroom facilities.
A structure that is primarily commercial but which also contains one or two dwelling units.
Any residential structure that contains a dwelling unit which does not fit the other structure codes, e.g. shack, garage.

A structure originally designed and built to contain one or more dwelling units which is designated as a nursing home, auxiliary hospital, care centre, lodge, etec. There are many seniors' residences being constructed that have suites with a bathroom and kitchenette containing a sink, bar fridge, microwave, etc. The suite must contain a full size fridge and stove to be considered as a separate dwelling unit. Otherwise, all suites included at one address and are part of this definition for lodges, care centres, or assisted living.
A structure where multiple residents are temporarily living and where the cooking is centrally provided for and which is not prepared by the residents, e.g. hospice, jail, etc.
